Lab: Confidence Intervals

36-600

We start by describing the functions that R provides that relate to probability distributions. We’ll start by giving the name of one of these: dnorm(). (You may have noticed that I tack on parantheses after function names. This is to make it clear to the reader that what is being referred to is a function and not, say, a variable.) We can split the name into two parts: - d: this means that the function is returning 𝑓𝑋(𝑥)fX(x), i.e., the probability density function value given the coordinate 𝑥x; and - norm: this means that we are working with the normal distribution.

First we’ll list the names of some common distributions:

R Name Distribution Parameters (See Help Pages For More)
binom binomial size (𝑛n) and prob (𝑝p)
pois Poisson lambda (𝜆λ)
norm normal mean (𝜇μ) and sd (𝜎σ)
t t df (𝜈ν)
exp exponential rate (𝛽β)
chisq chi-square df (𝜈ν)

And second we’ll list the prefixes that you use to accomplish various tasks:

Prefix What it Does
d returns the pdf 𝑓𝑋(𝑥)fX(x) or pmf 𝑝𝑋(𝑥)pX(x)
p returns the cdf 𝐹𝑋(𝑥)FX(x)
q returns the inverse cdf 𝐹−1𝑋(𝑥)FX−1(x)
r returns a random sample of data

What’s the cdf? It’s the cumulative distribution function, and we defined it in the notes as the probability that we sample a datum ≤𝑥≤x, where 𝑥x is the coordinate that we input into the cdf. For instance,

pbinom(5,size=10,prob=0.5)
## [1] 0.6230469

is the probability that we would observe 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, or 5 heads when flipping a fair coin 10 times, and

pnorm(60,mean=75,sd=10)
## [1] 0.0668072

is the probability of scoring 60 or less on a test whose true average score is 75, with standard deviation 10, if the test scores are truly normally distributed.

(The inverse cdf is, well, the inverse function: given a probability between 0 and 1, what is the associated 𝑥x coordinate? For instance,

qnorm(0.6,mean=75,sd=10)
## [1] 77.53347

tells us that on average, 60% of students will have a test score ≤77.53≤77.53.)

Before we play, we need to point out one more thing. Recall that you can define a vector using the seq() function. For instance,

seq(0,10,by=0.1)

defines the sequence {0,0.1,0.2,…,9.9,10}. As we’ll see, if we want to plot distributions, defining a sequence is a good way to start.

Question 1

Define an appropriate vector x and plot the probability density function 𝑓𝑋(𝑥)fX(x) on the y-axis versus 𝑥x on the x-axis for a normal distribution with mean 5 and standard deviation 2. To give you a hint as to how “wide” to define the sequence of values x, know that in general, nearly all the probability content of a distribution lies within three standard deviations of the mean. Put a little cushion on this, and define the sequence to stretch over a range of four or five standard deviations on either side of the mean. Oh…for plotting, you can create a basic plot via plot(x,y,typ="l"). (Eventually we’ll move to ggplot() for plotting, but let’s start here.)

# FILL ME IN
x<-seq(-10,20,by=0.1)
y<-dnorm(x,mean=5,sd=2)
plot(x,y,typ='l')

Question 4

What you will find is that each time you run the code in the code chunk for Question 3, you will get a different result. The reason is that every time you sample, you get a different dataset. This affects reproducibility. Hence, when you sample data, you should always set a random number seed first. You do that in R by calling the function set.seed() and passing in a number (your choice) as an argument.

Below, set the random number seed, sample five numbers from the distribution defined in Question 1, and display your sample. (You can do this by simply saying x, or by saying print(x).) Then repeat the process with the same random number seed. You should see that your five numbers are exactly the same.

# FILL ME IN
set.seed(89)
sample(x,5)
## [1]  9.6 11.4  7.9  5.8  4.2

Question 8

Construct a 95% two-sided confidence interval for the mean of the distribution that you just sampled data from above. (Forget that you know the mean is 10.) To do this, utilize the pseudocode from the notes:

f <- function(theta,[arguments])
{
  [cumulative distribution function]([arguments]) - q
}
uniroot(f,interval=[interval],[arguments],q=1-alpha/2)$root
uniroot(f,interval=[interval],[arguments],q=alpha/2)$root

Here, theta is 𝜇μ, or mu, the mean of a normal distribution. A few more details:

  1. We will assume that the standard deviation is known and is equal to 2. That means that the sample mean 𝑋¯X¯ is normally distributed (i.e., use pnorm()) with mean 𝜇μ (i.e., use mean=mu as one argument) and standard deviation 2/𝑛√=0.22/n=0.2 (i.e., use sd=0.2 as the other argument).
  2. The range of possible values for 𝜇μ is technically infinite, so use a wide range for interval that includes negative and positive values (i.e., interval=c(-100,100)).
  3. The additional arguments to f() are the variables that you need to get the function to run. Since we hardwired sd=0.2, we don’t need 𝜎σ or 𝑛n…but we do need q and we need the observed value of 𝑋¯X¯!
  4. Our confidence coefficient is 0.95, so 𝛼=0.05α=0.05.

If you run into issues, call me or a TA over!

alpha <- 0.05
# FILL ME IN
rn_mean <- mean(rn)

f <- function(mu, sample_mean, q) {
  pnorm(sample_mean, mean = mu, sd = 0.2) - q
}

q_lower <- 1 - alpha / 2
q_upper <- alpha / 2

ci_lower <- uniroot(f, interval = c(-100, 100), sample_mean = rn_mean, q = q_lower)$root
ci_upper <- uniroot(f, interval = c(-100, 100), sample_mean = rn_mean, q = q_upper)$root

ci_lower
## [1] 9.240264
ci_upper
## [1] 10.02428

Question 11

Over the last ten years, you have observed this many eruptions from a particular volcano:

0 2 1 0 1 2 0 0 1 1

You assume the data are Poisson distributed. What is a 95% two-sided confidence interval for the mean of this distribution? (That mean is conventionally denoted 𝜆λ, or lambda.)

We said we’d provide the details on sampling distributions. We did not lie.

  1. The statistic that you would use is the sum of the data (which has value 8).
  2. The sampling distribution for this statistic is a Poisson distribution with mean 10𝜆10λ.

So how would you change your code in Question 8?

  1. It’s a Poisson distribution: use ppois().
  2. The arguments to ppois() are the sum (call this x.sum) and the parameter value (call this lambda=nlambda). Change mu in the call to f() with nlambda.
  3. nlambda cannot be negative, so use, e.g., interval=c(0,100).
  4. At the end of each call to uniroot(), tack on /10 so that we get an interval for 𝜆λ rather than an interval for 10𝜆10λ.

In the end, your interval should be [0.412,1.567][0.412,1.567].

x <- c(0,2,1,0,1,2,0,0,1,1)
alpha <- 0.05
# FILL ME IN

f <- function(nlambda, x.sum, q) {
  ppois(lambda=nlambda,x.sum) - q
}

q_lower <- 1 - alpha / 2
q_upper <- alpha / 2

ci_lower <- (uniroot(f, interval=c(0,100), x.sum=sum(x), q = q_lower)$root)/10
ci_upper <- (uniroot(f, interval=c(0,100), x.sum=sum(x), q = q_upper)$root)/10

round(ci_lower,3)
## [1] 0.412
round(ci_upper,3)
## [1] 1.576

Question 13

In the notes, we computed a bootstrap confidence interval for the population mean 𝜇μ using the sample mean 𝑋¯X¯ as our statistic. What happens if we use the sample median instead? (The relevant R function is median().) Is the new bootstrap confidence interval wider? (Wider means that when we use this statistic, we are more uncertain about the mean!) Recall that the interval found in the notes is [4.527,5.268][4.527,5.268]. Note that all you need to do here is copy the code from the notes and switch out the mean for the median.

# FILL ME IN
set.seed(101)
x <- rnorm(20,mean=5,sd=1)
k <- 10000
x.bar <- rep(NA,k)
for ( ii in 1:k ) {
s <- sample(length(x),length(x),replace=TRUE)
x.bar[ii] <- median(x[s])
}
quantile(x.bar,probs=c(0.025,0.975))
##     2.5%    97.5% 
## 4.499510 5.418609
